Text.Value: Then look no further. The Zhentarim can protect the city - but only with Nine-Fingers out of the way.
What now?
You have my word.

EditorData.NodeContext: Faux-formality, with a little bow. She does mean it, but she's toying with us a little bit - we've just seen firsthand that she has no problem going back on her word.

Text.Value: Oh, let's.
Whatever you're planning to do to take down the Absolute - do it before that little worm of yours claims you.
Hm. Are you, by any chance, the bad smell that followed me up from the sewer?

EditorData.NodeContext: Sizing us up - knows we saw her in a compromising situation, taking money to betray Nine-Fingers
EditorData.logicalname: ROAH DIDN'T SEE US AT THE CISTERN

Text.Value: TO ARMS, ZHENTARIM - THE GUILD IS OURS FOR THE TAKING!

EditorData.NodeContext: Shouting to her troops to launch an attack

Text.Value: I did.
Enough talking. Get out of my way, or die.
The deal's not done yet. As it happens, I'd like to take this office for myself.
To arms, Zhentarim! The Guild is ours - once we clear out the vermin!

EditorData.NodeContext: Shouting to her troops to launch an attack

Text.Value: My new office. The chair could be a little comfier, and the desk definitely needs adjusting - but I'd say it'll do.
Betraying me? But, but... we had a deal.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Mock-whining and cringing - she saw this betrayal coming a long way off
EditorData.NodeContext: Mock-whining and cringing - she saw this betrayal coming a long way off

Text.Value: Whatever you saw, cool your heels a moment. Let's talk.

EditorData.NodeContext: Non-chalant - confident she can still turn this to her advantage.

Text.Value: You're not talking me into anything. Get out of my way, or die.
Besides that dragon's hoard you got from the Counting House?
A Guild under our control can do what Nine-Fingers failed to - drive the Absolute out of the city, once and for all.
I did what I was trained to - spotted the balance of power shifting, and nudged where I needed to make sure it fell our way.
The Zhentarim have been trying to crack Baldur's Gate for years, but Nine-Fingers' grip has been too strong. And look what it's come to.
Trade, why else? That gap-handed wench and her Guild held their monopoly for far too long.
Hah, a hero. There's a time for heroics, my friend, and a time for common sense. This was the latter.
Hm. I redecorate, I think. This place could do with some Zhentarim banners. Then we prepare.
You benefit too, don't forget. Go pick a fight with this god - we'll be there when you need us.
Her Guild is disorganised. Undisciplined. The cult broke them in a matter of days, while my Zhentarim still stand strong.
All right. We're indeed on the same side. Let's deal with Nine-Fingers.
We're all on the same side. If there are spoils to be split afterwards, well... I'm sure there's enough to share.
Ah - you survived. Which means my employers are dead, I take it? No matter - gives us a chance to talk.
Nine-Fingers is done. My Zhentarim stand ready to purge this place of everyone loyal to her.
I'm still not entirely clear what I get out of it.
Why does the Zhentarim care so much about Baldur's Gate?
You fail to see the bigger picture. Yes - they offered us money but more than that, they offered an opportunity. The money is a bonus.
So all I need to know is - does that include you, or not?
The Network has been looking for a toe-hold in this city for years, and I just gave them the whole damn leg-up.
Why are you working for the cult? They want to enslave everyone.
Fair enough. Can't say I'd have done different - though I think I'd have picked my moment a little better.
That depends. What are you offering me?
A more dependable ally than the current guildmaster.
When it comes time to fight the Absolute, you'll have a private army at your beck and call. With a newly-minted Sword-captain at its head, I suspect.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Sword captain' is a reference to herself - a faux-humble 'yours truly', as she's sure she'll get a promotion

Text.Value: Now the Guild can become a Zhent operation - and we'll have your back when the battle-horns start blowing.
A deal well done. Congratulations all around.
I'm loyal to whoever can help me save this city.
It's been a fruitful partnership, no doubt. Without Nine-Fingers clogging up the works, the Zhentarim have a clear run of the cities on the coast now.
Attack Roah.
Leave.
And you only had to collaborate with a death-cult to do it. Your superiors won't mind?

Synopsis: The player meets Roah in the Guildhall. The player can ask Roah about why they're working with Nine-Fingers. If the player witnessed the Roah being bribed by the Stone Man they can choose to side with Ninefingers or or Roah.
